detaileddescription.para: nu represents Poisson's ratio for isotropic linear elasticity. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[0].
q1 represents the first compliance parameter for Solidification Theory. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[1].
q2 represents the second compliance parameter for Solidification Theory. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[2].
q3 represents the third compliance parameter for Solidification Theory. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[3].
q4 represents the fourth compliance parameter for Solidification Theory. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[4].
n represents the exponent of the log-power law used in the compliance function of the hardened constituent. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[5].
m represents the exponent in the function describing the solidification of the material. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[6].

briefdescription.para: number of Kelvin units to approximate the viscoelastic compliance

detaileddescription.para: nKelvinBasic the number of Kelvin units used to approximate the viscoelastic compliance. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[7].

briefdescription.para: minimal retardation time used in the viscoelastic Kelvin chain

detaileddescription.para: minTauBasic represents the minimal retardation time in days used in the Kelvin chain to approximate the viscoelastic compliance. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[8].
ultimateAutogenousShrinkageStrain represents the ultimate autogenous shrinkage strain. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[9].
autogenousShrinkageHalfTime represents the autogenous shrinkage half time. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[10].
alpha represents a cement type and concrete composition dependent material parameter for autogenous shrinkage. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[11].
rt represents a cement type dependent material parameter for autogenous shrinkage. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[12].
ultimateDryingShrinkageStrain represents the ultimate drying shrinkage strain at zero relative ambient humidity. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[13].
dryingShrinkageHalfTime represents the drying shrinkage half time. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[14].
dryingStart represents start of drying in days. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[15].
hEnv represents relative ambient humidity. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[16].
q5 represents drying creep compliance parameter. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[17].

briefdescription.para: number of Kelvin units to approximate the drying creep compliance

detaileddescription.para: q5 represents the number of Kelvin units to approximate the drying creep compliance function. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[18].

briefdescription.para: minimal retardation time used in the drying creep Kelvin chain

detaileddescription.para: minTauDrying represents the minimal retardation time used in the Kelvin chain to approximate the drying creep compliance function. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[19].
castTime represents the time at which hydration starts with respect to simulation time. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[20].

briefdescription.para: ratio of simulation time to days

detaileddescription.para: timeToDays represents the ratio of simulation time to days. It is a reference variable to materialProperties[21].

detaileddescription.para: For a given linearized strain increment $\Delta\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$ at the old and the current time, compute the Cauchy stress and the algorithmic tangent $\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{\sigma}^{(n+1)}}{\partial\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^{(n+1)}}$.

parameterdescription.para: Algorithmic tangent representing the derivative of the Cauchy stress tensor with respect to the linearized strain
(Pseudo-)time increment from the old (pseudo-)time to the current (pseudo-)time
Suggestion for a new time increment

briefdescription.para: Implementation of a linear elastic material according to the B4 model by Bazant et al. (2015) generalized for 3D stress states.

detaileddescription.para: For further information see b4.
